<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880823-0087 </DOCNO><HL> BCE Unit to Buy Canada Phone Utility For $138.6 Million </HL><SO> </SO><CO> BCE CANDA </CO><IN> TNM TEL </IN><DATELINE> MONTREAL  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Canadian National Railways, the Canadian government-owned railway company, agreed to sell its Newfoundland telephone utility to Newfoundland Telephone Co. for 170 million Canadian dollars (US$138.6 million).    Under the terms of the agreement, Newfoundland Telephone will assume more than C$50 million long-term debt of the utility, Terra Nova Telecommunications Inc. Newfoundland Telephone is about 55%-owned indirectly by BCE Inc., the big Montreal telecommunications holding company.    Canadian National said Newfoundland Telephone's bid was the highest of five received. It also met all sales conditions, including pledges to honor labor contracts and maintain existing pension benefits and salary levels.    The ownership transfer is expected to take two to three months to complete.    Newfoundland Telephone said it will merge Terra Nova's operations with its own. Newfoundland Telephone is the dominant telephone utility in the province. Terra Nova serves about 400 rural communities.    Canadian National has also offered for sale Northwest Telephone Co., which serves parts of northern Canada. </TEXT></DOC>